      <h1>ZPT-Sharp Page Builder Quick-start</h1>
      <p>
        Zope Page Templates can also help you build <strong>static HTML</strong> websites that require
        absolutely no server-side technologies to run.  Write your pages using the
        <acronym title="Macro Expanded Template Attribute Language">METAL</acronym> and
        <acronym title="Template Attribute Language">TAL</acronym> technologies and then make use of
        ZPT-Sharp's page builder to assemble those components as an HTML website.
      </p>
      <h2>What the ZPT-Sharp Page Builder does</h2>
      <p>
        The ZPT-Sharp Page Builder is a commandline utility that takes a directory structure containing ZPT
        documents, parses each document using the core ZPT functionality and then outputs the rendered
        results of those documents into an output directory as static HTML documents.
      </p>
      <p>
        The main motivation to use the ZPT Page Builder is gaining access to the flexibility that METAL
        grants you in writing consistent pages, with reusable content regions, when the web hosting
        environment will not support any server-side technologies such as
        <a href="https://secure.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/wiki/Server_Side_Includes"
           title="Server Side Includes">SSI</a>.
        As an example, this documentation website was written 'offline' using ZPT and then assembled as a
        static HTML website using the Page Builder.
        <a href="https://github.com/CSF-Software-Development/ZPT-Sharp/tree/master/doc/documentation-website">The
        source for this documentation website</a> is a good place to start if you would like to see an
        example of how a ZPT-Sharp Page Builder is structured.
      </p>
      <h2>Using the ZPT-Sharp Page Builder</h2>
      <p>
        Firstly, you will want a grounding in
        <a href="quickstart-syntax.html" title="ZPT syntax quickstart">the syntax of ZPT pages</a>,
        paying particular attention to METAL, which is the technology that allows use and reuse of content
        <strong>macros</strong>.  TAL may also be useful, especially in combination with the
        <a href="page-builder/manual.html#options">options commandline parameter</a> but METAL
        will be the bigger draw for Page Builder projects.
      </p>
      <p>
        To assemble your directory structure of documents as a static HTML website, execute the page builder:
        <code class="block">CraigFowler.Web.ZPT.Builder.exe -o "output/path" -e ".html" "input/path"</code>
        This will read all of the files within the <code>input/path</code> (with a filename matching the
        pattern <code>*.pt</code>) as ZPT documents.  The page builder will render each of those
        documents, saving the output within <code>output/path</code> at the same location relative to the
        the input path, with the filename extension <code>.html</code> instead of <code>.pt</code>.
      </p>
      <p>
        For further information, take a look at the
        <a href="page-builder/manual.html" title="ZPT-Sharp Page Builder manual">full manual</a>.
      </p>
